<br />
1: This is war.  Attacking the WTC and the Pentagon go beyond mere acts of terrorism.  Whether committed by a nation or a single psychopath, these were acts of war.<br />
<br />
2: War is not about hate.  War is not about "bombing a country, any country".  It is not about "sending ragheads to hell".  THAT is terrorism.  We have to be above all that, or we are no better than those we seek to punish.<br />
<br />
As a Christian, believe me I fully understand the "turn the other cheek" sentiment, but that is not applicable in this situation.  The bible also teaches us that life is sacred, that we should defend life. If necessary we should be willing to go to war to defend life.  War is evil, but sometimes it is a necessary evil.  It is never to be taken lightly, but it should never be shirked if it is necessary.<br />
<br />
We, the US, did not instigate this war.  Those who attacked us Tuesday instigated this war.  They got their first strike.  Now it is incumbent upon us to determine who instigated this war.<br />
<br />
Once that is determined, the guilty parties have a choice: surrender, or face the consequences.  Those are the choices of anybody who is involved in war.  This conflict does not have to result in the bombing of Arab nations (if Arabians were in fact at fault) if those parties surrender.  But if they do not surrender, what choice do we have?  Let them be?  That is not an option.<br />
